{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "AutoChessManagerReview",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/HeroSimulation.cs",
      "description": "What is clamp? What is it for?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** \"Clamp\" means capping a value at a maximum so it can't exceed it -- here, `ClampClocks()` caps `AttackCooldown`/`MoveCooldown` at `1.0`. Why it's needed: without it, a unit that can't act for a long stretch (e.g. walking many ticks to reach the enemy) would keep accumulating cooldown past 1.0 -- \"banking\" charge -- then burst multiple actions the instant it's able to act. Clamping after each tick's action phases caps that bank at exactly one action's worth, so a unit that finally reaches the enemy attacks once immediately, not in a burst. See Combat.md Core Rules 7-8 and the \"Why the clamp is its own phase\" section for the full reasoning.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational).**\r\n\r\n----\r\nChange the name to CooldownCap() and state \"this function is to not allow the cooldown to be above 1\""
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/HeroSimulation.cs",
      "description": "Change the name to CooldownCap() and state \"this function is to not allow the cooldown to be above 1\"\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** `ClampClocks()` â†’ `CooldownCap()`, with the comment `// This function is to not allow the cooldown to be above 1.` above it, verbatim as requested. Updated the one call site in `AutoChessManager.cs`'s `ClampPhase()`. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 26
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "This function is too long. Separate into smaller function.\r\n\r\nDo we have a reason to use this in StartCoroutine(), should we use Update() instead?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Splitting is doable; the wrinkle is the `goto BattleEnd` inside the attack phase -- `goto` can't jump out of a separately-called method back into `BattleLoop()`. Plan: extract `ChargePhase()`/`AttackPhase()`/`MovePhase()`/`ClampPhase()`, with `AttackPhase()` returning a bool (battle ended) that `BattleLoop()` checks instead of using `goto`.\r\n\r\nOn coroutine vs. `Update()`: `StartCoroutine` + `yield return new WaitForSeconds(...)` is the idiomatic fit here specifically because the whole loop is \"do a tick, wait, do a tick, wait\" -- that reads top-to-bottom as one function. An `Update()`-based version would need to manually track elapsed time and \"which phase am I in\" as separate state across frames, since `Update()` has no equivalent to `yield return`'s \"pause here.\" Recommend keeping the coroutine.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Extracted `ChargePhase()`/`AttackPhase()`/`MovePhase()`/`ClampPhase()` plus a shared `CompleteBattle()` for the two end-of-battle paths (early wipe vs. tick-cap timeout). `AttackPhase()` returns `bool` instead of using `goto`. Kept `StartCoroutine`. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 94
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "This could be its function too, use \"OverTimePhase()\"\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Extracted the tick-cap block into `OverTimePhase(int ticks)`, matching `AttackPhase()`'s pattern -- returns `bool` (battle ended) instead of the loop deciding inline. `BattleLoop()` now reads `ticks++; if (OverTimePhase(ticks)) yield break;`. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 121
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": ".IsDefeated = the unit is dead, right?\r\nIt kinda confusing, use .IsDead instead.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Fair rename, with one catch: `Combat.md`'s \"States and Transitions\" section names this state **Defeated** specifically (paired with **Alive**) -- that's the GDD's chosen vocabulary, not an arbitrary code choice. If we rename, the doc should say the same word the code does.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Renamed `HeroDataRuntime.IsDefeated` â†’ `IsDead`, and every call site (`HeroSimulation.cs`, `AutoChessManager.cs`, `AutoChessHelper.cs`). `Combat.md`'s States and Transitions section updated to **Alive** / **Dead** (`IsDead`) so doc and code use the same word. `OnCombatantDefeated` (the event) is untouched -- this was about the property, not the event name.",
      "line": 188
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Setup.cs",
      "description": "Okay, this part is about data in AutoChessManager, correct?\r\n\r\nThen, move it to new calss AutoChessData.\r\n\r\nI want to separate data from manager. Is that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Makes sense for part of it. Of the manager's 4 private fields, only `_combatants`/`_grid` are genuinely \"world state\" shared with `AutoChessHelper`'s queries. `_playerPlacements` (pre-battle setup buffer) and `_battleRunning` (the manager's own lifecycle guard) are a different kind of thing -- bundling everything into one `AutoChessData` risked recreating a mixed-responsibility grab-bag instead of fixing one. Also, unlike the earlier-rejected `AutoBattleCtx` proposal, this is safe from the back-reference concern: `HeroSimulation` never touches `AutoChessData`, only the manager and `AutoChessHelper` do.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** New `AutoChessData` class (`Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessData.cs`) holds `Combatants` and `Grid` only. `AutoChessManager` holds one `_data` field instead of separate `_combatants`/`_grid`; `_playerPlacements`/`_battleRunning` stay on the manager. `AutoChessHelper`'s three methods now take `AutoChessData` as one parameter instead of `combatants`/`grid` separately. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome.\r\n\r\n---\r\nThe part where it initialize HeroDataRunTime, GetHP(). Those should be in AutoChessData.\r\n\r\nSince they work directly relate to the data.\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Added `AutoChessData.AddCombatant(HeroDataSeed, id)` (builds the `HeroDataRuntime` + wraps it in `HeroSimulation`) and `AutoChessData.GetCurrentHP(id)`/`GetMaxHP(id)`. `AutoChessManager.Setup.cs`'s `SetCombatants()` now just loops calling `_data.AddCombatant(...)`; its `GetCurrentHP`/`GetMaxHP` are one-line wrappers delegating to `_data`. The manager keeps the public API surface and the event/log side effects (`OnCombatantsSet`, the setup log line) -- those aren't data operations. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 12
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Setup.cs",
      "description": "Hey, this also use data related logic.\r\nIt should be move to AutoChessData too.\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Moved `GetCombatantSnapshots()`'s body into `AutoChessData.GetCombatantSnapshots()`. `AutoChessManager.Setup.cs`'s version is now a one-line delegate: `public List<CombatantSnapshot> GetCombatantSnapshots() => _data.GetCombatantSnapshots();`. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 94
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Setup.cs",
      "description": "Explain clearly what is this for?\r\nExplain SetPlayerPlacements() too.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** `SetPlayerPlacements()` just stores where the player put their units before the battle starts -- `BattleBoardManager` calls it once the player finishes dragging heroes onto the board, and it merges those hex coordinates into `_playerPlacements`. It doesn't touch the simulation at all; `BeginBattle()` reads `_playerPlacements` later to actually place units on the grid.\r\n\r\n`GetAutoEnemyPlacements()` is the enemy-side counterpart, but computed instead of stored: it walks the non-player combatants and assigns them hex coordinates row-by-row, starting from the first row past the player's side (`_data.Grid.PlayerRowCount`), wrapping to the next row when a row fills up. It's read by two different callers -- `BeginBattle()` (to place the enemies in the simulation) and `BattleBoardManager` (to spawn the enemy sprites) -- from the exact same computation, which is why the comment above it calls this \"the single source of truth\": both the visuals and the sim always agree because they're not two separate placement decisions, just two readers of one.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational).**\r\n---\r\n\r\nIsn't that weird? Why would we have a simulation differ by player and enemy, shouldn't we use HeroSimulation as a SST?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED â€” via `/code` (GDD-gated, since this changes a data model).** Enemy placement is now authored input, same standard as player placement. `EnemyDatabaseStub` (`Assets/Scripts/Battle/Testing/EnemyDatabaseStub.cs`) holds `List<EnemyPlacementEntry>` -- each entry pairs one `HeroDataSO` with a `HexCoord` -- instead of a bare `List<HeroDataSO>`. `GetAutoEnemyPlacements()` now zips `EnemyDatabaseStub.GetUnits()`/`GetPlacements()` against the seeded enemy combatants by index instead of computing a row-fill; an enemy with no authored entry logs an error rather than falling back to a computed position (per your call on the fallback question). `Hero.md` updated (Core Rule 8 + the Seed-sources interaction row) since this changes `EnemyDatabaseStub`'s documented contract; `Combat.md` needed no change -- its only constraint (one shared placement method) still holds. Re-authored `BattleTest.unity`'s two enemies (Knight/Archer) at their prior row-fill coordinates and verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 64
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Setup.cs",
      "description": "But you still separate SetPlayerPlacement and GetAutoEnemyPlacements.\r\nIf they use the same standard, shouldn't they be group togeher by the same function?\r\n\r\nThose do something similar, it should use the same function.\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** \"Same standard\" was about where the data comes from (authored, not computed) -- not about how it's delivered, and those two still differ in shape. `SetPlayerPlacements(Dictionary<string, HexCoord>)` is a **setter**: `BattleBoardManager` pushes in positions it just learned from live drag-and-drop input, so it needs a parameter to receive them and somewhere (`_playerPlacements`) to store them until battle start. `GetAutoEnemyPlacements()` is a **getter**: it has no external input to accept -- it reads `EnemyDatabaseStub`'s authored list straight off the GameObject and returns a fresh `Dictionary` each call, storing nothing. A shared function would need either a setter that ignores its own parameter half the time or a getter forced to accept a dictionary it never uses -- same conclusion the earlier `SetUnitPositions`/`GetAutoEnemyPlacements` DRY question reached, now re-confirmed under the authored-placement design.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational).**\r\n----------------\r\n---------------\r\nokay, so it look like this:\r\nPlayer: input => read input => put on the board\r\nEnemy: existed position => read it => put on the board\r\nIs that correct?\r\nIf yes, make both for both side. Player/Enemy should be able to receive same input. Both should also read from existing position.\r\n\r\nIs taht make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED â€” via `/code` (GDD-gated).** Full symmetry, per your call on both scoping questions (enemies get real drag-input capability; player also gets an authored default). New shared `HeroPlacementEntry` (`Assets/Scripts/Battle/Testing/HeroPlacementEntry.cs`, replaces the enemy-only `EnemyPlacementEntry`) -- both `StudentRosterStub` and `EnemyDatabaseStub` now hold `List<HeroPlacementEntry>` and expose `GetPlacements()`. `AutoChessManager` gained `SetEnemyPlacements()` (mirrors `SetPlayerPlacements()`) and a new `_enemyPlacements` buffer, plus `GetPlayerPlacements()`/`GetEnemyPlacements()` (renamed from `GetAutoEnemyPlacements()`) -- each merges live-set input over its stub's authored default (input wins per-unit when both exist). `BeginBattle()` and `BattleBoardManager` now call these instead of touching `_playerPlacements`/`GetAutoEnemyPlacements()` directly. `Hero.md` (Core Rule 5, Rule 8, Interactions table) and `Combat.md` (BattleBoardManager row) updated. Re-authored `BattleTest.unity`'s `StudentRosterStub` with a default formation (Knight/Archer at (0,0)/(1,0)) since its field type changed. Verified: full battle identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win), plus a direct edit-mode check confirming both defaults resolve correctly with no input, and both `SetPlayerPlacements()`/`SetEnemyPlacements()` overrides correctly take priority per-unit.\r\n\r\nNote: `SetEnemyPlacements()` is manager-level API only, matching how `GetActiveTraits()` was added \"for a future HUD panel, not used in combat\" -- no drag-UI for enemies was built (`BattlePlacementController` still only highlights player-side tiles). Say if you want that UI wired up next.",
      "line": 41
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Setup.cs",
      "description": "This is only for setting the placement for player before start the game, correct?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Confirmed -- `SetUnitPositions()` (as it was named) is specifically for player placement, injected by `BattleBoardManager` from wherever the player dragged units. Enemy placement is the separate `GetAutoEnemyPlacements()`, computed algorithmically rather than externally provided. See the next comment's resolution for the naming fix this motivated.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational, folded into the next comment's fix).**",
      "line": 54
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Setup.cs",
      "description": "We have SetUnitPosition() for player's hero placement at start, and GetAutoEnemyPlacements() for enemy's placement at start too.\r\n\r\nIs that correct? If yes, Group them together to fix DRY.\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Correct on the pairing, but there's no actual DRY violation to fix -- the two methods aren't duplicated logic. `SetUnitPositions()` *stores* externally-provided placements; `GetAutoEnemyPlacements()` *computes* a layout algorithmically and returns it. Different shapes (setter vs. computed getter), so there's no repeated code block to merge away. What IS real: the naming is asymmetric -- \"Set...Positions\" vs. \"Get...Placements\" uses two different words for the same concept, and only one name says which team it's for. That's what made this pairing non-obvious enough to ask about in the first comment.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED â€” via a rename, not a merge.** `SetUnitPositions()` â†’ `SetPlayerPlacements()`. Both methods now say \"Placements\" and both name their team (Player/Enemy) -- a reader sees they're a matched pair without reading both bodies. Updated the one external caller (`BattleBoardManager.cs`). Verified with a full battle: identical outcome.",
      "line": 54
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Testing/EnemyDatabaseStub.cs",
      "description": "Also what is stub mean?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** A \"stub\" is a lightweight placeholder implementation that stands in for a system that doesn't fully exist yet -- not a real content pipeline, just enough to unblock testing. `EnemyDatabaseStub` is literally that: a `SerializeField` list on a component, not a real enemy-encounter authoring system. The class comment already flags this (\"Enemy-side seed for the vanilla engine\"), and `Hero.md`'s Open Questions table notes the same thing from the design side: a proper non-Hero/encounter content type is deferred until it's actually needed -- this class is the interim stand-in.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational).**",
      "line": 9
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Setup.cs",
      "description": "Standalone seed path doesn't clear. Be more specific and short.\r\n\r\nI also don't like the name of the variable for those stub. It is database and stub, use better direct name e.g. playerStub, enemyStub.\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** `stub`/`database` â†’ `playerStub`/`enemyStub`, as requested. Comment shortened from 4 lines to 2 and now says what the method does up front: \"Builds the roster from this GameObject's StudentRosterStub + EnemyDatabaseStub, if it hasn't been seeded already. Errors out naming exactly what's missing, rather than silently producing an empty board.\" Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 68
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Traits.cs",
      "description": "Everything here don't need to be in Manager, no?\r\nit could be move to its dedicated class Trait.cs\r\n\r\nIs taht make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** New `Trait.cs` (`Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/Trait.cs`), `internal static class Trait`, mirroring `AutoChessHelper`'s pattern -- stateless, takes `AutoChessData` as a parameter rather than holding a reference. Holds `ApplyTraitBonuses()`, `GetActiveTraits()`, and the private `CountTraits()` helper (moved verbatim). `AutoChessManager.Traits.cs` is now two one-line delegates: `ApplyTraitBonuses() => Trait.ApplyTraitBonuses(_data)` and `GetActiveTraits(team) => Trait.GetActiveTraits(_data, team)` -- the manager keeps its existing API surface (`BeginBattle()` and `BattleBoardManager` call sites unchanged). Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win) and identical trait-bonus log lines (Fighter +ATK 6 at breakpoint 2, both teams).",
      "line": 14
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.Traits.cs",
      "description": "Do we still neeed AutoChessManager.Trait?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** As a *file*, yes -- even at 2 lines it matches how the rest of the manager is already organized: `.Setup.cs` groups the setup API, `.Debug.cs` groups debug-only API, `.Traits.cs` groups the trait-facing API. Folding those two delegate lines into the main `AutoChessManager.cs` would work too, but it'd be the one place the manager's API isn't grouped by concern the way everything else is. As a *class holding logic*, no -- that already happened; it's just the two one-line delegates now.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational).**",
      "line": 9
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/TraitDataSO.cs",
      "description": "Should we leave method in SO?\r\nI never know we could have method here.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Yes -- a `ScriptableObject` is an ordinary C# class underneath (`class TraitDataSO : ScriptableObject`), so it can carry methods the same as any class. `GetActiveBreakpoint()` is a pure query -- it reads `Breakpoints` and returns a result, never mutates the asset -- so keeping it on `TraitDataSO` means every caller gets the same \"highest satisfied breakpoint\" logic for free instead of each reimplementing that loop. `HeroDataSO.ToCombatData()` (Hero.md) is the same pattern elsewhere in the project: a read-only projection method living on the authored asset it reads from.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED (informational).**\r\n",
      "line": 35
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/TraitDataSO.cs",
      "description": "We have Trait.cs already.\r\nSo move this method there too.\r\n\r\nIs taht make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** The justification I gave for leaving `GetActiveBreakpoint()` on the SO leaned on `HeroDataSO.ToCombatData()` as \"the same pattern\" -- you pushed back that `ToCombatData()` itself is questionable, since it makes the authored `HeroDataSO` reference `HeroDataSeed`, a downstream pipeline type. That's a fair, different critique: `GetActiveBreakpoint()` only returns `TraitBreakpoint`, defined in the same file/layer as `TraitDataSO` -- no seed-layer coupling exists there, so it stays. `ToCombatData()` does have that coupling, so it moved.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** `GetActiveBreakpoint()` stays on `TraitDataSO` (no seed coupling to fix). `HeroDataSO.ToCombatData(Team team)` relocated to a new stateless `HeroDataSeedFactory.ToCombatData(HeroDataSO hero, Team team)` (`Assets/Scripts/Battle/Data/HeroDataSeedFactory.cs`) -- `HeroDataSO` no longer references `HeroDataSeed` at all. `StudentRosterStub`/`EnemyDatabaseStub` (the seed sources) call the factory instead of `hero.ToCombatData(team)`. `Hero.md` updated (Core Rule 3, Rule 5, Interactions table, Edge Cases, Acceptance Criteria) via `/code` â†’ `/read-gdd` (PARTIAL verdict) since this changes a documented contract; `Combat.md` and `best-practices.md`'s example comment updated too. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 37
    }
  ]
}